{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3f0f4242-0fc6-4b2b-ae83-e44f1f32e062","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic. Here's the general guidance based on .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS writes to `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** The OS will write a `core.<pid>` file to `/cores/`.\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, ensure SIP isn't blocking it. On macOS 11+, you may need to:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **For NativeAOT specifically**, since managed debugging metadata is limited, focus on native stack traces in `lldb`. You can use `bt` (backtrace) and `image list` to map addresses back to your binary.\n\n> **Note:** `createdump` is bundled with the CoreCLR runtime but is **not included** in NativeAOT deployments, so relying on macOS's native core dump facility is the standard fallback.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"acb34f82-c85c-45cf-a31b-d4da0f9d9490","outputTokens":329,"requestId":"5022:D09D:284071:322976:69F5552B"},"id":"bafca586-ee75-448c-8eff-63ec1ccd1c3e","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:36:56.067Z","parentId":"bbf02748-6c5a-4680-8436-e3a37020121d"}
